<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-448-659  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 448 659.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 17 1990 v12 n37 p44(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apps can access remote databases via interface: user insulatedfrom database languages. (System 7 primer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lach, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Apple's new System 7.0 operating system for the Macintoshmicrocomputer contains a Data Access Manager that provides astandard interface for Macintosh applications to access a varietyof remote databases.andP;  It allows the user to deal with the databasewithout learning the language of the particular database.andP;  TheData Access Manager creates queries in the command languages ofthe most widely used database servers.andP;  There are actually twoapplication interfaces: the high-level interface prepares andsends the query, receives the results and translates it into textautomatically; the low-lowel interface requires these functions tobe performed by the user or the application.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   System 7.0 (Operating system) (design and construction)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Operating SystemsData Bases.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   How Data Access Manager works. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>